<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-10-11T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-10-11T11:00:00-05:00" n="499" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d499">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72112/5055: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-10-11T16:00:00+00:00"><hi rend="italic">October
                                            11, 1917—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October
                                    11—3:45 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>My despatch no. 4822, September 25 Admiralty Marshal states: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>“I understand from the Procurator General who has forwarded
                                        me letter from Blockade Minister that when American
                                        Government approaches British Government concerning the
                                        release of seizures involving American interests to American
                                        citizens British Government <pb facs="0699" n="609" xml:id="pg_609"/> will be prepared to give same
                                        advantages as heretofore afforded other Allied
                                        Governments”.</p>
                                </quote></p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Skinner</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>